## The other half of ancient Egypt is directly overhead.

You will spend your days in Egypt looking down and around — at tombs, at temples, at hieroglyphs cut into stone. But the people who built all of it spent their nights looking up, at a sky most of us have never actually seen. They had no light pollution, no screens, nothing between them and the stars — and so the night sky was not a backdrop to their world. It was central to it. They named it, worshipped it, farmed by it, and carved it into the ceilings of the very temples you've been walking through.

Drive twenty minutes past the last streetlight on a moonless night, and you get it back.

## A dark sky, a telescope, and someone who knows

Most "stargazing" trips are a bonfire and a vague wave at the sky. This isn't that. We take you privately to a genuinely dark spot — the kind where the Milky Way is bright enough to cast a faint shadow — set up a proper telescope, and hand you a guide who can actually find things: the rings of Saturn, the mountains and craters along the edge of the moon, a distant cluster of stars that left its light on its way to you before the pharaohs were born.

And then the context, which is the part you can only get here: these are the exact stars the ancient Egyptians steered and worshipped by. Sirius, the brightest of them, whose reappearance in the dawn sky once announced the flooding of the Nile and the start of their whole year. The constellations they turned into gods and painted onto tomb ceilings. You are not looking at a pretty sky. You are looking at their calendar, their religion, and their map.

> They lay under this sky and built a civilisation around it. For one night, you get to lie under the same one.

## Warm, quiet, and quietly enormous

It's a gentle evening. Blankets, hot karkade, no schedule, and the vast, total silence of the desert after dark — which is its own experience before you even look up. There is nothing to achieve and nowhere to be. You lean back, the guide points, your eyes adjust, and slowly the sky fills with more stars than you have seen in your entire life put together.

Bring a warm layer and a little patience. Some guests tell us, at the end of a trip full of temples, that the night they remember most was the one where they didn't look at a single monument — and just looked up instead.
